******
[2] Preventive measures in Negros Occidental
Date: Mon 16 Sep 2019 (Manila time)
Source: Manila Times [abridged, edited]
https://www.manilatimes.net/2019/09/16/news/headlines/negros-bans-hogs-pork-from-luzon/616756/


The provincial government of Negros Occidental has banned for 90 days the entry of live hogs, pork meat and pork products from Luzon, where cases of the highly contagious African swine fever (ASF) have been confirmed.

Gov. Eugenio Jose Lacson approved Resolution 19-05 passed by the provincial ASF's task force. The body recommended the temporary ban that covers pork and pork products originating from, processed or manufactured in Luzon.

"The governor will issue a memorandum addressed to me and to all municipal and city mayors for the implementation of Resolution No. 5," Renante Decena, provincial veterinarian, said.

Last week [8-14 Sep 2019], the Department of Agriculture (DA) officially confirmed that ASF was the cause of swine deaths in the provinces of Rizal and Bulacan [both in Luzon, eastern and northern to Manila, respectively] last month [August 2019].

Lacson appealed to travelers not to bring pork products from any area in Luzon to Negros Occidental.

In enforcing the prohibition, the task force underscored the "pressing need to protect the swine population of the province from being infected with the dreaded ASF disease in particular, and the PHP 6 billion [USD 115.5 million] provincial swine industry in general."

"Pork and pork products from these provinces, whether fresh, processed or canned may carry directly ASF viruses, which would introduce the disease into Negros Occidental," the task force said.

Figures from the Provincial Veterinary Office (PVO) showed that Negros Occidental's annual swine production is 510 000 heads. The province is the country's top backyard hog producer.

Lacson has directed the task force to carry out ASF prevention and control measures, enhance biosecurity practices in all ports of entry and swine production facilities, and coordinate and cooperate with the appropriate national government agencies in case of a suspected outbreak.

The ASF task force also urged operators and owners of hotels, resorts and restaurants in the province to refrain from throwing out food wastes or leftovers that can be used for swine feeding.

On Sunday [15 Sep 2019], Agriculture Secretary William Dar appealed to backyard hog raisers [throughout the Philippines] to report sick and dead pigs to their respective municipal or city veterinarians to prevent the spread of animal diseases, including the dreaded ASF.

He urged all swine raisers to allow the veterinary officers to undertake the safety measures, who will in turn coordinate with the Bureau of Animal Industry (BAI) to determine the cause of sickness or death.

Dar made the appeal over the discovery of dead pigs along Marikina River and a creek in Quezon City [in Luzon]. "It was utterly irresponsible on the part of the backyard raisers, as they did not only violate current laws, but their [wrongdoing] also spread the disease pathogens much faster," he said.

He warned that those who irresponsibly [dumped] the dead pigs could be punished under the law. Dar said sickly animals deserve proper care and adequate treatment. If they die, owners have to observe strict protocols on the disposal of carcasses.

"The Department of Agriculture [DA], through the BAI and the National Meat Inspection Service, in partnership with the private sector, particularly with commercial hog raisers' groups, local government units, the PNP (Philippine National Police) and military, has taken all the necessary measures to manage, control and contain the possible spread of ASF and major swine diseases," the DA chief said.

"The irresponsible dumping of dead pigs simply adds [fear] to the public, and this should not be tolerated. The perpetrators must be punished in accordance with the law," he added.

Marikina City Mayor Marcelino Teodoro on Sunday [15 Sep 2019] said the city government would file charges against those who dumped dead pigs in the river.

[Byline: Eugene Y. Adiong & Eireene Jairee Gomez]

